<font color="#FF0000">A TRIBUTE TO ETHYL &amp; AL MCKEON</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 14 23:09:47 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I said above that I would share a bit of my gifts from Korea, and their impacts on me.  In the early 1960's I was asked by Al and Ethyl McKeon of Stayton, Oregon to be the Godfather of their adopted boy from Korea.  I agreed, and started to get to know him.  It took a long time, but he finally started coming out of his shell.  He now has a family of his own here in Oregon.<br><br>
Getting to know him, his brother and two sisters provided me with some moral guidance that others in the military did not have.  It ultimately kept me out of some of life's worst troubles, and gave me a perspective on life, on the role of sex in the military, and on the need for personal responsibility over and above obligations to the military and its customs.<br><br>
Without this unique perspective, freely given by a grand lady, Mrs. Ethyl McKeon (Al passed away after a long illness), I would have suffered much more greatly because of my Vietnam experience.  I have said elsewhere (see &quot;Forum&quot;) that I did not suffer from Post Traumatic Stress Syndrome from my Vietnam experience.  She is the main reason why.<br><br>
I write this because Mrs. McKeon passed away suddenly a week ago, while in her 80's.  She had lived life to its fullest, gardening and volunteering at a hospital (and this after a 30+ year career as a teacher at a School for the Deaf), and traveling (last year to Hawaii, where she took a submarine ride).  She always had time to talk to me, and always was optimistic.  <br><br>
I owe her a lot.  Maybe if we all could look back and see the Ethyl McKeons of the world, and think of the joy and happiness they brought to us, we would be less stressed.  And maybe if me emulated her, the world would be happier.
